Follow the steps below to send your observability data to Logit.io

<Steps>
  ## Metrics

  Configure Telegraf to ship Google Cloud Load Balancing metrics to your Logit.io stacks via Logstash.
  
  ### Install Integration
  <InstallIntegration/>
  ### Set Credentials in GCP

  <SetGCPCredentials intro="Google Cloud Load Balancing is an exclusive collection of services embedded within Google Cloud. It's meticulously structured for managing the distribution of network traffic across several servers, bolstering secure and efficient interaction across numerous software components in a cloud-oriented infrastructure."/>
  
  ### Install Telegraf

  <InstallTelegraf />

  ### Configure the Telegraf input plugin

  <TelegrafStackDriverInput metric_type="loadbalancing.googleapis.com"/>

  ### Configure the output plugin

  <TelegrafOutputPlugin />

  ### Start Telegraf

  <StartTelegraf />

  ### View your metrics
  <LaunchStack stackType="metrics" source="Google_Cloud_Load_Balancing_Metrics_via_Telegraf" utmMedium="metrics" utmCampaign="telegraf-GoogleCloudLoad Balancing-metrics" />

  ### How to diagnose no data in Stack

  <DiagnoseNoData />
</Steps>

## Telegraf Google Cloud Load Balancing metrics Overview

For precise monitoring and thoughtful evaluation of Google Cloud Load Balancing metrics across 
distributed systems, the requirement for a powerful and efficient metrics management tool like 
Telegraf is essential. Telegraf, as an open-source server agent, is esteemed for its capacity 
to accumulate and relay metrics from an array of sources, which includes active load balancing 
instances, databases, and related applications.

With an extensive suite of input plugins, Telegraf allows users to accumulate varied metrics 
such as request counts, latency, error rates, and more. These metrics are crucial to comprehend 
the performance of Google Cloud Load Balancing. For the safekeeping and investigation of these 
gathered metrics, organizations can exploit Prometheus, an open-source monitoring and alerting 
toolkit, highly regarded for its flexible query language and robust data visualization abilities.

The procedure to transfer Google Cloud Load Balancing metrics from Telegraf to Prometheus 
involves configuring Telegraf to render metrics in Prometheus's format, followed by directing 
Prometheus to scrape these metrics from the Telegraf server.

Once the metrics are successfully assimilated into Prometheus, a more profound analysis and 
visualization can be executed using Grafana. As a top-tier open-source platform renowned 
for its monitoring and observability attributes, Grafana integrates seamlessly with Prometheus. 
It enables users to generate dynamic, interactive dashboards for a comprehensive examination 
of the metrics data, yielding a profound understanding of performance trends and potential 
issues within Google Cloud Load Balancing.

If you need any further assistance with shipping your log data to Logit.io we're here to help 
you get started. Feel free to get in contact with our support team by sending us a message via <IntercomButton text="live chat" /> & we'll be happy to assist.